WEBVTT

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:05.600
Hey everybody, thanks so much for joining us today for our Workflows with Posit Teams session.

00:00:06.160 --> 00:00:13.040
If this is your first time joining us, we do host these workflows the last Wednesday of every month

00:00:13.040 --> 00:00:18.080
and so if you ever want to go back and check out the recordings, I think we've had about seven of

00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:26.639
them so far, but today you will learn from Gordon Shotwell, Senior Software Engineer at Posit,

00:00:26.639 --> 00:00:32.880
who is joining us to show how to use Posit Connect as an end-to-end Python platform

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:38.240
for hosting internal machine learning models. I'll be hanging around in the background here,

00:00:38.240 --> 00:00:43.919
so if you have any questions, feel free to put them into the chat. I'll also put a Slido in

00:00:43.919 --> 00:00:48.639
there where you can ask anonymously, but with that, thanks again for joining us and I'll turn

00:00:48.639 --> 00:00:55.279
it over to Gordon. My name is Gordon Shotwell. I'm a Software Engineer at Posit and I mostly

00:00:55.279 --> 00:01:02.880
work on Shiny for Python, but before I worked at Posit, I worked in industry building tools for

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:06.800
training, deploying, and monitoring machine learning models and I learned a couple of

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:10.800
patterns with Posit Connect that I think are particularly useful and I wanted to go through

00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:17.760
some of those today. So let's just get started by taking a look at this modeling code and this is a

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:24.959
very simple, maybe probably in these days, this day and age, primitive text classification model

00:01:24.959 --> 00:01:31.839
that basically classifies text based on the words that are in that sentence to determine whether

00:01:31.839 --> 00:01:37.519
it's about electronics or not. And here we have sort of the modeling code, break the model into

00:01:37.519 --> 00:01:43.839
a training and test set, fit the model, and then print out some accuracy, some model statistics.

00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:48.959
And the question here is, say I'm happy with this model and I want to share it with other people,

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:55.360
how should I do that? And in particular, how should I share it with all the different groups of people

00:01:55.360 --> 00:01:59.680
that might need to interact with either this model or the data that underlies this model somehow?

00:02:01.279 --> 00:02:06.480
So this is a kind of the way I would sort of break it up in terms of this sort of imaginary

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:10.000
situation where I'm building a model, I want to share it with other people, and I can think of

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:20.479
five groups that need to use this model. So the first group is me, like the modelers, me and the

00:02:20.479 --> 00:02:26.399
team of people who actually generated this model. Second group is leadership, who might want to

00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:31.919
get model statistics or have a sense of how this model is performing on the latest set of data.

00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:42.080
Third one is the data team. These might be people who use code to score the text that they're

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:46.320
encountering in their own data sets. And then finally, we have these other two groups. One is

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:51.520
a group of annotators. This is a group of people who might be annotating data to provide me with

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:56.559
more training data and improve the quality of my models. And there's this last group that's just

00:02:56.559 --> 00:03:02.080
kind of other systems that might come up. You know, other people using other programming languages,

00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:06.639
maybe somebody who's working on the website might need to call this model for some reason.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:11.279
And all these groups have different needs and, importantly, different interfaces.

00:03:11.839 --> 00:03:16.720
So modelers and the data team, they're probably both using Python. They might have some people

00:03:16.720 --> 00:03:22.000
using R, but in this case, in this sort of example, say they're all using Python. Leadership,

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.000
they probably just want to see a static site. You know, they don't need something super interactive,

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:32.320
they just need to see something that gives them a little printout of statistics. And finally,

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:36.479
we have these annotators, and they're probably not technical, so they're going to need more of

00:03:36.479 --> 00:03:40.960
a full-featured web app. And these other systems are going to interact with some programming

00:03:40.960 --> 00:03:43.919
language that maybe we don't know now or won't know about in the future.

00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:50.559
One of my most sort of important principles when thinking about these types of systems

00:03:50.559 --> 00:03:56.320
is this rule, which is APIs before UIs. So when we look at this group of people,

00:03:56.880 --> 00:04:01.600
see that there are a few different groups that are using something you might call an API. It's

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:08.800
a code-first interaction with this product. We have these Python users and these other systems,

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:14.800
which might use some type of code. And the reason why I think APIs before UIs is such a good rule

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:20.720
is that code interfaces are way easier to build than GUIs. They just have fewer parameters. You

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:26.000
don't need to worry about centering something or making the UI kind of intuitive. You can just

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:29.760
build the code and have people interact with the code. Because they're easier to build,

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:35.119
they're easier to change and iterate upon. This means that if you're kind of working mostly on

00:04:35.119 --> 00:04:39.760
an API, you're going to be able to make more changes more quickly to center in on the right

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:43.200
interaction, the right data model, and the right type of user flow

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.799
for your particular product. And my experience doing this for a number of years is that a good

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:54.480
API will usually create a good UI, both in terms of the simplicity of the code and also how

00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:59.200
intuitive it is. Once you've kind of centered on that right API, the right interaction for your

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:04.799
problem, the GUI that serves that type of interaction is pretty obvious most of the time.

00:05:04.799 --> 00:05:11.359
The opposite is not true. I've seen a lot of times people build a GUI first. And in doing that,

00:05:11.359 --> 00:05:16.559
they kind of just sort of throw different things into some type of programming data model or some

00:05:16.559 --> 00:05:23.519
type of interface. And trying to build intuitive code interface using those same data structures

00:05:23.519 --> 00:05:27.440
can be really awkward. So if you ever tried to analyze web data as a data scientist, this is

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:33.200
kind of why you get this big giant blob of JSON that's not particularly well structured for your

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:39.920
purpose, right? So if you ever have the option of building the code interface first before doing any

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:45.040
type of GUI work, I really recommend doing this. Doesn't always happen, but in this case we do,

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:50.239
right? We have these three groups of people are interested in code. They're also probably

00:05:50.239 --> 00:05:55.679
our earliest stakeholders, so we might want to serve them first. Okay, so one way of distributing

00:05:55.679 --> 00:06:01.839
this model is to use a Python package, right? I could put this model in a Python package

00:06:01.839 --> 00:06:08.160
and have that package be installed from something like Posit Package Manager or Nexus or some other

00:06:08.720 --> 00:06:15.519
package hosting system. But this creates a few problems. And I would say there's three

00:06:15.519 --> 00:06:20.880
main problems. The first is that packages are necessarily really hard to authenticate and

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:28.640
authorize. So usually when you look at internal repositories that are like PyPy-like repositories,

00:06:28.640 --> 00:06:32.799
they don't have particularly sophisticated security controls on who can download

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:38.480
those packages. But the bigger problem is that once those packages are downloaded from those

00:06:38.480 --> 00:06:44.559
repositories, they're just in the wild. There's no real way for us to control who has access to them.

00:06:44.559 --> 00:06:49.839
We can't create fine-grained controls. For example, give some people access to one Python

00:06:49.839 --> 00:06:55.279
function in the package and other people access to another one. And if the individual human who

00:06:55.279 --> 00:07:02.000
just downloaded that package shares it inappropriately or leaves their laptop open

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:07.359
and untended, anything that's in there, including the model or any type of data that's in that

00:07:07.359 --> 00:07:14.399
package is going to be exposed, right? So if we're working on a model that maybe includes some

00:07:14.399 --> 00:07:20.000
sensitive intellectual property or might encode some sensitive data or expose some sensitive data,

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.839
that's going to be a really big problem, right? We want to have the ability to authenticate the

00:07:23.839 --> 00:07:29.440
model when it's called. And the second big problem with packages is that they always require user

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:34.959
input to update. So if I were to distribute this model in a Python package just by itself,

00:07:35.600 --> 00:07:41.519
if I ever changed the model or updated it or changed some part of how that model is called,

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:47.760
I would need to ask all of my downstream users to update their installation. And they would need to

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:51.279
do that probably in a lot of places. So they may need to update it in all the different virtual

00:07:51.279 --> 00:07:54.959
environments they have on their computer. If they deployed assets to Posit Connect,

00:07:54.959 --> 00:07:59.839
they would need to update all those. It becomes an enormous hassle. And the final reason is that

00:07:59.839 --> 00:08:04.320
that would need Python, right? Most of our users are kind of comfortable using Python,

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:08.079
but some of them maybe aren't. Maybe I have some R users at my company. Maybe there's a

00:08:08.079 --> 00:08:13.920
Scala group that wants to call this model. And adding Python to their build environment is

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:20.320
maybe going to cause some problems. An alternative, and what I'm going to choose here, is to use an

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:28.320
API. Basically, host this model as an API on Posit Connect and have some wrapper functions

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:32.719
that call that API. And this is going to give me a couple of major advantages. First is that

00:08:33.679 --> 00:08:37.679
I'm going to solve all three of the problems that I just expressed, right? I'm going to

00:08:37.679 --> 00:08:43.520
be able to update that model in one place by re-uploading it to Posit Connect. I'll be able

00:08:43.520 --> 00:08:51.359
to authenticate access to the API, both the top-level domain and also I can authorize any

00:08:51.359 --> 00:08:56.719
of the endpoints that people call. And finally, it's going to be language independent. Every

00:08:56.719 --> 00:09:01.919
programming language has the ability to wrap and call APIs. So if I can put something up as an API,

00:09:01.919 --> 00:09:09.520
then I'm going to be able to give access to everybody. So I'm going to go through kind of

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:14.080
the overall diagram here, and then I'm going to take it piece by piece and show you the code

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:19.599
that I developed for these projects. So this is kind of the big picture of what I'm trying to do.

00:09:20.159 --> 00:09:24.799
And I have kind of three groups here. So the leadership, I have data scientists who might

00:09:24.799 --> 00:09:30.000
use both an R or Python package, and then I have these annotators. And I'm also showing

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.919
the interface that these people are going to be using. So this leadership group, they're going

00:09:33.919 --> 00:09:39.679
to be looking at a Cordo, a rendered Cordo document. These data scientists are going to

00:09:39.679 --> 00:09:46.400
be interacting through a Python or R package with an API, and then the annotators are going to be

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:51.760
interacting with a Shiny app. The API in turn is going to call a data store, and I'll show you what

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:55.359
that is, but I would recommend probably this should be a database that sort of lives outside of

00:09:55.359 --> 00:10:02.080
Connect. But everything else can exist on Connect. And the reason why I really love Connect for this

00:10:02.080 --> 00:10:07.599
purpose is that it gives me a kind of safe space that I'm able to deploy all these different types

00:10:07.599 --> 00:10:14.239
of assets for all these different users without needing to have a lot of conversations with either

00:10:14.239 --> 00:10:20.719
DevOps, security, or any kind of regulatory situation at my company. Since I have Posit

00:10:20.719 --> 00:10:26.080
Connect set up, there's this one-time investment of getting that through, all the different layers

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:30.479
of approval that you need to implement something like this. You can secure it in a way that is

00:10:30.479 --> 00:10:35.119
compliant with all of your company's policies, but once you've done that, you can just deploy these

00:10:35.119 --> 00:10:42.080
things to this product. It makes it a really useful prototyping solution both for sort of

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:47.280
small things like a Shiny app or a Jupyter notebook, but also for these larger

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:52.080
interconnected systems. I can validate that this whole thing works with just me, the

00:10:52.080 --> 00:10:56.080
data scientist, doing the work. I don't need to involve other people getting the infrastructure

00:10:56.159 --> 00:11:02.640
or putting that infrastructure. All right, so this is a lot. So we're going to start with this API

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:08.960
and show you kind of the endpoint for this API,

00:11:12.239 --> 00:11:19.440
which is this API here. And so you see this API is a fast API, and it has a few different

00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:27.919
endpoints. So I have the ability to append training data to this dataset. I can

00:11:27.919 --> 00:11:35.359
score the model, I can update the model, I can get the last updated date, and I can query the data.

00:11:35.359 --> 00:11:41.119
And what's nice about this is that this is interactive Swagger documentation, so it'll

00:11:41.119 --> 00:11:45.919
give me kind of some information about what this is expecting. In this case, it has no parameters, and

00:11:45.919 --> 00:11:52.159
it just gives you a successful response or gives you a string response. And I can try it out. So I

00:11:52.159 --> 00:11:58.400
can just click execute, and it's going to give me both the curl command that I used to call this,

00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:04.080
the request URL, and then also the response for this particular thing. And for some of these,

00:12:04.080 --> 00:12:11.520
that gets a little bit more complicated. So I chose fast API for one main reason,

00:12:12.479 --> 00:12:17.919
and the main reason that... So fast API has a few great benefits. One is that it's very fast,

00:12:17.919 --> 00:12:22.799
but in my case, I don't particularly care about this being a fast API. It's a very simple one,

00:12:22.799 --> 00:12:29.119
so many of them are going to be fast enough. But what fast API gives you is this, which is

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:36.479
a clear example of what data type this is expecting. So in this case, it's expecting a list

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:44.719
and then a JSON object with a key value pair of text with text annotator annotation. These two

00:12:44.719 --> 00:12:50.320
need to be string, and this one needs to be a Boolean. And the way that is produced, if I go

00:12:50.320 --> 00:13:01.119
back to my... go over to my API code here, is by creating these pedantic models that tell the API

00:13:01.119 --> 00:13:05.760
what it should expect. So here I'm able to define... I'm defining this training data class,

00:13:05.760 --> 00:13:12.239
which is just a very simple sort of key value model with these three keys and these three

00:13:12.239 --> 00:13:22.320
value types. And then when I create my Python function, I'm able to refer to that. I'm saying

00:13:22.320 --> 00:13:28.880
this data... I'm using type annotation to say this data is expecting a list of training data elements.

00:13:29.520 --> 00:13:35.679
And that list of training data elements is then going to generate this expected value.

00:13:35.679 --> 00:13:38.799
Not only will it sort of generate that from the documentation perspective,

00:13:38.799 --> 00:13:46.159
but it's going to validate that for me. So if somebody sends a malformed... sends a different

00:13:46.159 --> 00:13:53.520
type of payload to this API, it's going to give me a 422 error. So for example,

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:03.440
if I take this annotator one out here, I try executing it, the response I get is a 422.

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:08.880
And what that means is that the API is expecting a particular form of data,

00:14:08.880 --> 00:14:13.200
and you didn't supply that data. So it's going to give you an informative error for that,

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:17.200
without me, the programmer, needing to write any of that validation. I don't need to do anything.

00:14:17.200 --> 00:14:22.960
I just need to declare in the FastAPI type annotation that that's what I'm expecting,

00:14:22.960 --> 00:14:24.400
and then I'm going to get that result back.

00:14:27.200 --> 00:14:30.799
So I'm not going to go through this code in too much detail. This is going to be a pretty high

00:14:30.799 --> 00:14:37.039
level sort of architectural planning thing. But the basic... but a couple of... but one thing I

00:14:37.039 --> 00:14:42.880
did want to point out here is that I'm storing all this data on an on-disk SQLite database,

00:14:42.880 --> 00:14:48.960
and that's mostly just to keep everything on Connect without building up too many dependencies.

00:14:49.599 --> 00:14:53.919
But that particular... if you were doing this in reality, I would recommend pulling that out to

00:14:55.679 --> 00:15:00.239
another datastore. So that's kind of... so to go through some of these models a little bit,

00:15:00.239 --> 00:15:05.200
I have append training data, which just takes a list of those training elements

00:15:06.159 --> 00:15:14.239
and sends them to... appends them to my SQLite datastore. I have a model scoring endpoint,

00:15:14.239 --> 00:15:21.359
which opens up the latest model that's been uploaded and returns a single score. So it's

00:15:21.359 --> 00:15:27.440
taking a text, a bit of text, and returning that score. I have the ability to update this model.

00:15:27.440 --> 00:15:33.840
So I have an update model endpoint, which takes both the machine learning model and the vectorizer

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:42.000
to sort of turn your text into the right features. And finally, I have a query data endpoint, which

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:48.159
is just sending a query and getting a result of that query, and a couple of test endpoints to just

00:15:48.159 --> 00:15:51.359
let me understand, you know, is this API working and things like that.

00:15:53.919 --> 00:16:00.159
The way that you... so the way that this model is intended to be used, for the most part,

00:16:00.159 --> 00:16:04.719
is I want to allow people to... some people to upload models, I want to allow people... some

00:16:04.719 --> 00:16:08.640
people to append data, and I want other people to be able to score the model or query it.

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:14.159
And when I'm doing that, I... this is kind of this notion of authorization, right? So I want

00:16:14.159 --> 00:16:20.559
to be able to sort of authenticate everybody who's joining, who's seeing this API, but I want

00:16:20.559 --> 00:16:26.559
to authorize a couple of people to do some endpoints. And I'm able to do that with this

00:16:27.119 --> 00:16:33.280
validate and validate access function here. So this function is basically asking,

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:40.320
is user user in this control list? And if it's not, raise a 401. And that

00:16:42.960 --> 00:16:49.760
user user is generated by this function, which is get current user, which just looks for the

00:16:50.080 --> 00:16:57.599
information in the header that's passed to PositConnect. And what that is going to allow

00:16:57.599 --> 00:17:04.000
me to do is basically say, get the person who's accessing or viewing this API and respond with

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:12.640
either you can access it or you can't as a 401. So the result of that is that I have a couple of

00:17:13.359 --> 00:17:17.920
endpoints, which are available to everybody, like score model. So if you were to log open this up

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:22.880
and try to score this score model, you would be able to do that. So you could try this out.

00:17:22.880 --> 00:17:28.000
You could say, I am a computer. I think it's probably not going to give me a very good score

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:34.400
here. But here you see, I'm getting a 200 with the score from that model. But if you were to try to

00:17:34.719 --> 00:17:41.680
to update a model or to query the data, you're going to get a 401 error. I won't get a 401 error

00:17:41.680 --> 00:17:45.119
because I'm sort of one of the people who are, who's, who's allowed to view it.

00:17:50.880 --> 00:17:55.680
Okay, so that's the, that's mostly the API. And

00:17:56.640 --> 00:18:00.000
this has a couple of benefits. So the main couple of benefits we've just talked about are it allows

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:04.319
me to authorize these features and allows me to keep my model in one place so that everybody who's

00:18:04.319 --> 00:18:08.959
using it, when they call the API is kind of keeping, getting the right up-to-date model.

00:18:09.599 --> 00:18:14.079
But it's not particularly user-friendly, right? And, and the main reason why it's not user-friendly

00:18:14.079 --> 00:18:19.760
is that most of, most data scientists are not, they're not, they're not, they're not, they're not

00:18:20.319 --> 00:18:26.000
And the main reason why it's not user-friendly is that most of, most data scientists are not

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:31.599
actually that comfortable with interacting with APIs, I would say, right? They don't have sort

00:18:31.599 --> 00:18:37.599
of in the back of their mind, like these are what all this HTTP status codes mean. And in order to

00:18:37.599 --> 00:18:41.680
give any kind of validation that they're calling this API correctly, you have to send something

00:18:41.680 --> 00:18:46.479
back and forth to the API, which can be a little bit difficult. What we really want to do is we

00:18:46.479 --> 00:18:51.280
want to be able to surface errors easily and give people a lot of kind of like hand-holding to help

00:18:51.280 --> 00:18:56.959
them through calling and interacting with this API properly. Let's go back to our diagram here,

00:18:56.959 --> 00:19:01.040
right? So this API, usually when you're building APIs, you kind of want to make them predictable

00:19:01.040 --> 00:19:04.880
and pretty strict, but not that friendly. They don't, it's not that important that they're give

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:10.640
you great error messages or sort of guide you along a happy path. And in order to give that sort

00:19:10.640 --> 00:19:16.000
of hand-holding, give that sort of like ergonomics that you want when you're building a sort of

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:21.199
delightful user experience, it's usually a good idea to kind of wrap that API in a package of some

00:19:21.199 --> 00:19:25.040
kind. This could be a package of any programming language, right? Because this API is generic.

00:19:25.760 --> 00:19:27.680
But in this case, I'm going to do just a Python one.

00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:37.280
So I have my Python package here, and this package has just one class. And this is the

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:45.920
way that I personally really like writing API wrappers, which is I have an init method that

00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:53.280
populates the top level URL and the headers. This is really useful. For example, if I wanted to

00:19:53.280 --> 00:19:59.520
change this URL, I would have it changed in one place. Or if I wanted to develop against a local

00:19:59.520 --> 00:20:06.719
running, I could set this URL to localhost. And then I typically have methods that are

00:20:06.719 --> 00:20:12.640
for each HTTP request type that I'm going to use. In this case, I'm only using post and get.

